Windows Log in help? ; I have set and reset the password on my administrator account, but every time I restart the computer it NEVER asks me for the password. Whats the point of having one if all you have to do is restart the dam it to get into it. Im I just missing something really easy...help ; Normally, the Administrator User is the highest Authority level on the computer...so, normally, using this account must be with care as you have full control over the PC, including installing, uninstalling, deleting, etc

Regarding Windows automatically logging in without asking for a password, this is because its been configured to automatically login with a default Username and Password (password coould be blank)..

Also, not getting a list of users to choose which one to log on with is due to that the Administrator Account is a Member of "Administrators" & "Debuggers" groups and not the "Users" group, so, it will never show up in the list of logginig on...

To reconfigure this, you can do any of the following options:
[1]
- Create another account that is a normal user by oopening User Accounts from under control panel and choose create a new user account (Limited Account);

[2]
Add the Administraot user in the "Users" Group by doing the following (any mistake can cause problems...please follow steps carefully):
- Right-click on My Computer and choose Manage;
- Under "Computer Managerenet", on the menu on the Left, double-click "Local Users and Groups" to open a sub-mneu;
- Click on "Users" from the sub-menu;
- On the right side, right-click on the "Administrator" User and choose Properties;
- Click on the second tab which says "Member Of";
- Click on "Add";
- On the following Screen, at the bottom left is a button called "Advanced", click on it to expand this screen with more options;
- Now, on the right side of the screen, in the middle is a button named "Find Now", click on it;
- Below, a table shows up with two colomns, Name (RDN) and In Folder--under the Name (RDN), scroll down until you find the group called "Users" with an icon of 2 faces NOT 1 [they are arranged alphabetically]--then click on it and choose "OK";
- Then click "OK" again on the next 2 screens...

[3]
- Open Control Panel, then User Accounts, as you probably did before to reset the Administrator Password;
- Under the User Accounts screen, choose the third option, "Change the way users log on or off";
- Two options are now avialable, if they are both checked (selected) unselect the first one, then Apply changes...

PS: As far as I could remember, that this 1 requires another user account to be available as well to run...

PPS: This option will change the login screen to the old pre-Windows XP style...

Hope this answers your question...
